The 12 best commuter cars of 2024

18/12/2024

City cars are a staple on UK roads and are improving in quality all the time, with each new model designed with more practicality and personality in mind than the last.

While walking, cycling, or using public transport is better for the environment and therefore encouraged by many workplaces, a large proportion of us still rely on driving to get to work.

According to the 2024 Commuter Census by Mobilityways, 45% of UK commuters drive to work in single-occupancy vehicles (SOVs). This includes both petrol/diesel and hybrid/electric vehicles.

The time spent commuting hasnt changed much in recent times, remaining at an average of 59 minutes in 2024 (source: Mobilityways). That said, one thing that helps make the daily slog to the office easier is doing it in a high-tech, attractive city car.

With so many city cars on the road and more set to be released over the next year, it can be difficult knowing which model is the best for you or even what to start looking for.

Thats why weve compiled a list of the top twelve cars for commuters, based on key features like their price points, fuel economy and driver assist features, to help you find the best cars for commuting.

What makes a good commuter car in terms of fuel efficiency?

The best commuter cars are compact, practical, and easy to drive around town whether its due to responsive driver assist technology, advanced driver assistance features, or competitive fuel economy.

The combination of small, yet capable, engines and basic chassis set-ups mean that urban cars have always offered great value, with some better at making long-distance motorway trips than others. Regardless, all city cars have ease of driving, character, and versatility as key selling points. Explore our range of city cars to rent today.

Heres some of the technologies that are worth keeping an eye out for in your next car:

  • City Mode: City Mode is designed to help drivers navigate tight corners and compact parking spaces under pressure. At just a push of a button (typically found on the steering wheel), the power assistance is increased for more responsive and lighter steering at low speeds.

  • Regenerative Brakes: When you hear commuter car you probably think of primarily diesel models that are renowned for their fuel economy, but electric cars can offer just as much efficiency when it comes to regenerative brakes. These work to recuperate power in stop-start traffic, ultimately prolonging battery life.

  • Adaptive Cruise Control: These systems automatically adjust the speed of your car to maintain a safe distance between you and the car ahead, which is crucial during rush hour. It can also be called Intelligent Cruise Control or Adaptive Cruise Assist.

  • Forward Collision Warning: Forward Collision Warning alerts the driver to an impending forward impact, with alerts typically taking the form of either audible beeps or flashing lights. Some models offer it alongside Pedestrian Detection for added safety.

When buying a city car, its also good to look for specific safety features particularly if youre looking for something that doubles as a family vehicle.

Some key safety features to look out for include electronic stability control, autonomous emergency braking, isofix points, airbags, lane-keeping assist, lane-keeping technology and other visibility aids.

If they dont come as standard on the entry-level models, check whether theres a safety options pack that you can add on to your next car.

What is the best urban car for commuters?

Mazda 2

The Mazda 2 1.5 Skyactiv is a fantastic choice for commuters seeking a stylish, efficient, and fun-to-drive car. Its sleek design and premium interior create a pleasant driving experience, while its fuel-efficient engine and low running costs make it an economical choice. The Mazda 2s nimble handling and responsive steering make it a joy to drive in city traffic, and its compact size makes it easy to park.

Additionally, its advanced safety features provide peace of mind for daily commutes.

Toyota Aygo

A staple on UK roads, the Toyota Aygo is a solid commuter car that stands out from the crowd thanks to its dramatic styling and punchy performance. Available as either a standard three-door model or a sizable five-door vehicle, drivers can pick from five trim levels and a host of colour combinations for added personalisation. The entry-level model offers 71bhp which is more than enough for pottering around town and commuting to work, while the five-speed manual gearbox is cleverly configured to easily manage motorway stretches or steep hills.

Audi A5

The Audi A5 is a sleeker-looking version of the A4 saloon, and sports three different suspension options depending on which trim is selected. For those who prefer active handling and a firmer ride, sports suspension is available on the popular S Line and Black Edition trims. When it comes to engines, the entry-level diesel is nippy enough when sending power to the front wheels, while the more potent diesel benefits from Audis innovative quattro four-wheel-drive and an automatic gearbox as standard. Theres also a classy, minimalist interior and a host of safety assist technologies to boot. One of the advanced driver assistance technologies available in the Audi A5 is traffic jam assist, which enhances the driving experience during congested conditions.

Citroen C3

The beloved Citroen C3 takes all the elements you know and love in other small cars, and enhances them with an extrovert styling thats sure to stop traffic around town consisting of numerous colour combinations, quirky door mirrors and trademark air bumps. But Citroen doesnt favour style over substance the 108bhp 1.2-litre petrol (badged PureTech 110) is more than capable on city roads, with all models paired with a manual gearbox as standard. The rear seats offer impressive comfort and spaciousness, making it suitable for adult passengers and family use. And thats not all; theres also super-soft suspension, intuitive controls and an innovative infotainment system.

Volkswagen Golf GTE

The Volkswagen Golf GTE offers the best of both worlds for commuters, combining efficient electric driving with flexible petrol power. Its plug-in hybrid powertrain allows for zero-emission commuting in urban areas, while its petrol engine provides extended range for longer journeys. The Golf GTEs spacious and comfortable interior, advanced technology features, and refined driving experience make it a practical and enjoyable choice for daily commutes.

Furthermore, its strong performance and dynamic handling make it a fun car to drive, even outside of commuting.

Hyundai i10

The Hyundai i10 is a fantastic choice for a commuter car due to its compact size and excellent fuel efficiency. Its small dimensions make it easy to manoeuvre through city traffic and find parking spots, saving you time and stress during your daily commute. The i10s fuel-efficient engines also help you save money on fuel costs, making it an economical option for frequent drivers. Additionally, the Hyundai i10 offers a comfortable and well-equipped interior. A spacious cabin provides ample room for both passengers and luggage, while the modern infotainment system keeps you connected on the go. The i10 also comes with a range of safety features, including airbags, anti-lock brakes, and electronic stability control, ensuring your peace of mind during your daily commute.

Tesla Model 3

The Tesla Model 3 is a fantastic commuter car offering a blend of efficiency, technology, and driving pleasure. Its impressive range allows for stress-free daily commutes, while the extensive Supercharger network provides convenient charging options. The Model 3s sleek design and comfortable interior create a pleasant driving experience, and its advanced Autopilot features can ease the burden of traffic jams and long motorway journeys. Additionally, its low running costs and potential tax benefits make it an attractive choice for UK commuters.

Kia Picanto

The entry-level Kia Picanto comes with five doors as standard, so is perfect for those who like to carpool, with drivers able to choose between three punchy petrol engines and either a manual or automatic transmission. Theres also a particularly firm suspension, which allows the Picanto to corner more alertly than the majority of its rivals.

Dacia Sandero-Stepway

The Dacia Sandero Stepway excels as a commuter car due to its combination of affordability and practicality. Its compact size makes it easy to manoeuvre through city traffic and find parking spots, while its raised ride height offers improved visibility and a smoother ride on uneven roads. The spacious interior comfortably accommodates both passengers and luggage, ensuring a pleasant commute. Additionally, the Sandero Stepways fuel efficiency helps keep running costs low, making it an economical choice for daily driving.

Beyond its practicality, the Sandero Stepway offers a surprising level of comfort and features. The comfortable seating, user-friendly infotainment system, and modern design elevate the overall driving experience.

Peugeot 508

Considered one of the safest cars on the road, the fastback Peugeot 508 boasts slick styling touches like frameless side windows and eye-catching daytime running lights. Its available as a plug-in hybrid version that combines a punchy petrol engine with an efficient electric motor, and offers a range of around 39 miles, and theres also a dynamic diesel- and petrol-powered variants. The 508 also benefits from the trademark i-Cockpit layout which keeps driver usability paramount, with Apple CarPlay, sat-nav and wireless charging standard across the range.

Fiat 500 Electric Car

The Fiat 500 Electric is an excellent choice for a commuter car, offering a blend of style, efficiency, and practicality. Its compact size makes it ideal for navigating city traffic, while its electric powertrain ensures smooth and silent journeys.The 500 Electric boasts impressive range, making it suitable for daily commutes without range anxiety.Additionally, its low running costs and zero tailpipe emissions contribute to a sustainable and cost-effective driving experience.

Beyond its practicality, the Fiat 500 Electric offers a stylish and retro-inspired design that stands out on the road. Its comfortable interior and user-friendly technology further enhance the overall driving experience. With its combination of performance, efficiency, and style, the Fiat 500 Electric is a compelling choice for urban commuters seeking a fun and eco-friendly ride.

Honda Civic

Another staple on UK roads, the latest Honda Civic boasts a stylish revamped interior and improved refinement, with drivers able to choose between two petrol engines and one diesel variant. Diesel engines provide better torque and fuel economy, making them a practical choice for commuters and those requiring more performance during longer trips. There are a staggering seven trim levels to choose from, meaning theres equipment and features that are designed to suit most drivers. Comfort is paramount on the interior as the steering wheel offers plenty of adjustment, and crucial safety features like a reversing camera and rear parking are standard on the lower trims.

Summary

The city car class is densely populated with safe, reliable, and popular models both new and in the used car market. In fact, you are awash with options from petrol and diesel engines to hybrids and full electric if thats your preference.

If youre happy with your current car but want to improve the reliability during rush hour on your daily commute, you may want to take a look at our blog post on tech that keeps you focused while driving.
